1

00:00:02,049  -->  00:00:05,434
When building multiple linear regression models,

2

00:00:05,434  -->  00:00:07,694
there's a number of problems that may arise.

3

00:00:07,695  -->  00:00:10,190
But defining what constitutes as a problem,

4

00:00:10,189  -->  00:00:13,269
is depending on what your model is going to be used for.

5

00:00:13,269  -->  00:00:17,469
Are you using your model to understand how your x and y variables are related?

6

00:00:17,469  -->  00:00:21,259
Are you using your model to best predict the response variable?

7

00:00:21,260  -->  00:00:23,210
Or are you interested in finding

8

00:00:23,210  -->  00:00:27,380
which variables are really useful in predicting your response?

9

00:00:27,379  -->  00:00:30,515
Each of these could have a number of problems that arise with it.

10

00:00:30,515  -->  00:00:33,590
Depending on which aspects you're most interested in,

11

00:00:33,590  -->  00:00:37,950
this can help determine which problems you actually care about addressing.

12

00:00:37,950  -->  00:00:40,592
In Introduction to statistical learning,

13

00:00:40,591  -->  00:00:42,740
the following problems are identified.

14

00:00:42,740  -->  00:00:48,545
First, a linear relationship may not exist between your response and predictor variables.

15

00:00:48,545  -->  00:00:51,188
Second, you might have correlated errors.

16

00:00:51,188  -->  00:00:54,718
Third, you might not have constant variance of your errors.

17

00:00:54,718  -->  00:00:59,210
Fourth, you might have outliers or leverage points that hurt your model.

18

00:00:59,210  -->  00:01:02,429
Or last, you might have more linearity.

19

00:01:02,429  -->  00:01:06,674
There are entire books and courses aimed at each of these potential problems,

20

00:01:06,674  -->  00:01:11,075
so the discussion of these topics and this class will not be exhaustive.

21

00:01:11,075  -->  00:01:14,030
But Chapter three dives into each of the above.

22

00:01:14,030  -->  00:01:18,670
I'm going to take a more industry focused approach towards addressing these problems,

23

00:01:18,670  -->  00:01:23,745
where Introduction to statistical learning takes on a more academic approach.

24

00:01:23,745  -->  00:01:28,003
A summary of the academic approach is provided in the following concept.

25

00:01:28,003  -->  00:01:30,890
But if you want to see how this is applied in practice,

26

00:01:30,890  -->  00:01:34,000
feel free to move on to the applied portion that follows.
